<h2 id="toc6"><span>About the Artist</span></h2>
<div class="scp-image-block block-center" style="width:600px;"><img src="http://scp-wiki.wdfiles.com/local--files/barredowl-s-kick-ass-art-page/headerNEW.png" style="width:600px;" alt="headerNEW.png" class="image" />
<div class="scp-image-caption" style="width:600px;">
<p>Pictured: me</p>
</div>
</div>
<p>Hey all, I'm <span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/barredowl" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(6001754); return false;"><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=6001754&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1609721434" alt="barredowl" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=6001754)" /></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/barredowl" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(6001754); return false;">barredowl</a></span>, a somewhat ambitious artist and turtleneck sweater enthusiast. As of now, I mostly draw via a little program by the name of Photopea. It's trash, sure, but it's <em>my</em> trash, you know?</p>
<h2 id="toc7"><span>The Process</span></h2>
<h4 id="toc8"><span>Pixel Art</span></h4>
<p>So usually, when I'm thinking of drawing an SCP, I usually tend towards a situation which I can easily display. For example, maybe the interview log in <a href="/scp-3980">SCP-3980</a>, or the gramophone from <a href="/scp-3939">SCP-3939</a>. If it's just a simple humanoid, I usually just draw their face. I occasionally just draw a character from the SCP, such as the Masquerade figure from <a href="/scp-4430">SCP-4430</a>.</p>
<p>After I've fully convinced myself that drawing that part of the SCP is going to be fun, I head over to a <a href="https://lospec.com/palette-list">palette list</a> and select something that catches my eye (usually a four-color palette, since that's the easiest to handle in Paint 3D). I download it via a .txt file and head over to Paint 3D to select the individual colors using a hex code.</p>
<p>Then, I shift the canvas to an appropriate size. If it's smaller (i.e, a humanoid picture) I usually choose a 30x30 canvas. If it's larger (i.e a situation I want to illustrate) I shoot for a 60x60. Then, I get to drawing, expand the canvas to 300x300 once it's finished, and publish it here!</p>
<h4 id="toc9"><span>Drawings</span></h4>
<p>I usually just draw SCPs that I like, to be honest. Nothing really special. The only real fun tidbit I have to share about the process is that most of my drawings, if colored, are sampled from a <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Giorgio_de_Chirico">Giorgio de Chirico</a> painting. You can find the painting sampled from <a href="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/1/1b/De_Chirico%27s_Love_Song.jpg">here</a>!</p>
<h2 id="toc10"><span>Contact Information</span></h2>
<p>If you want to reach out to me, whether it be commissions, words of praise, or your deepest, darkest confessions, here are some of the sites you can contact me from!</p>
<table class="wiki-content-table">
<tr>
<th>Platform</th>
<th>Username</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Wikidot</td>
<td><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/barredowl">barredowl</a></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>IRC</td>
<td>barredowl</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Reddit</td>
<td><a href="https://www.reddit.com/user/barredowl_">barredowl_</a></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Instagram</td>
<td><a href="https://www.instagram.com/barredowl_/">barredowl_</a></td>
</tr>
</table>
<p>For future reference, I typically don't charge money for commissions, but if you want me to draw something, that article better be damn good or draw-able.</p>

